1. Are Being In A Bad Shape And Not Being Smiley Correlated?

we can create 2 series of data:

  • Smile column of Badly Shaped Pistachios : \(P(K|B=1)\) where K is the random variable for Pistachios Smile.
  • Smile Column of Well Shaped Pistachios : \(P(K|B=0)\)

comparing the distribution of these, can show us whether the conditional distributions are similar or not. If \(H_0\) is correct, it means that the variables are independant.

We can do this by using a wilcoxon test, or a chisquared test. Both are implemented Below.

#wilcoxon
S1=filter(peste,bad.shekli==1)$naakhandan
S2=filter(peste,bad.shekli==0)$naakhandan
wilcox.test(S1,S2)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  S1 and S2
## W = 5946900, p-value = 0.02941
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
# independent chisq.test

tbl=table(peste$naakhandan,peste$bad.shekli)
chisq.test(tbl)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  tbl
## X-squared = 4.3868, df = 1, p-value = 0.03622

The test results show that the mean of these two series are different, however, given the size of the dataset the p-value isnt small enough. Thus, we cant determine whether \(H_0\) is correct or not.

3. Using Parametric And None-parametric Tests to Investigate The Difference Between The Shape Size

Here We want to find out about the relation between X=: seed weight and Y=: how well shaped the pistachio is. X is a continues variable and its marginal distribution can be assumed to be normal, however, Y is a discrete ordinal variables. having this in mind, and the fact that their variance isnt necessarily equal, well select two test to investigate our hypothesis which is stated in a more clear manner below:

  • The seed of the good-looking pistachios is bigger/heavier than the seeds of the bad-looking ones.

Parametric test:

We want to compare the means of two samples, weights of good-looking pistachios and WEIGHTS of bad-looking ones. ]n each set, the distribution of sample mean can be assumed normal, since weight is a continuous variable measure a lot of times. so, We can use an upaired t-test.

t.test(peste$vazne.maghz,peste$bad.shekli,"greater")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  peste$vazne.maghz and peste$bad.shekli
## t = 27.674, df = 10524, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is greater than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.5177111       Inf
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 0.6899242 0.1394949

this shows that \(H_0\) isnt correct. \(H_1\) says that the distributions are different and the mean seed weight of good-looking pistachios is bigger than bad-looking ones.Thus, our primary assumption was false .

Non-parametric test:

we can use the wilcoxon test which is the equivalent of the ttest above, it just assumes that the seed weight sample distribution might not be normal.

wilcox.test(peste$vazne.maghz,peste$bad.shekli,"greater")
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  peste$vazne.maghz and peste$bad.shekli
## W = 83745000, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is greater than 0

Note that by adding the greater argument, were setting \(H_1\) to be: \(W_G<W_B\) and so, we achived the same results by using the non-parametric test as well.

this plot compares the distributions:

highchart() %>% 
  hc_add_series_boxplot(peste$vazne.maghz,by=peste$bad.shekli) %>% 
  hc_add_theme(hc_theme_google()) %>% 
  hc_title(text="Comparision of seed weight between good and bad looking pistachios")

Hypothesis Test:

It seems that the weight distribution within and amongst the sacks might not be homogeneous. Meaning that according to the samples we have from each of the sacks, one sack could be statistically heavier than the others,

facing this problem, we can ask two type of questions.

  • Are the mean weights of sacks statistically different?
  • How much the mean weights are different? (numerically)

To answer these question, we can design a Hypothesis Test like below:

\[H_0 : \mu_1=\mu_2=...=\mu_n\]

\[H_1 : \forall \quad i,j \in [1,n] \quad \mu_i\neq\mu_j\]

by using ANOVA method, we can asnwer both of our questions with the results of this test.

5. Investigating The Homogeneity

Well be implementing the anova method once manually and once by using the R function aov() .

5.1 Manual Implementaion

  1. Variance of sample means (Inter-Sacks Variance)

We have to calculate the mean weight of each sack and then the variance of these means.

# Creating a new dataframe grouped on "nemoone" with the mean weights of each nemoone.
peste %>% group_by(nemoone) %>% summarise(wm=round(mean(vazne.peste),3))%>% select(box=nemoone,wm)->SampMean

#the mean of sample means
Mean=round(mean(SampMean$wm),3)

#calculating the variance of sample means, manually!
SampMean %>% mutate(dif=wm-Mean) %>% mutate(absdif=dif^2) ->SampMean
Sx2=round(sum(SampMean$absdif)/(length(levels(factor(SampMean$box)))),4)

#note that:  length(levels(factor(SampMean$box))) = r-1   where r is the number of sacks

So the variance amongst the boxes/sacks is:

\[s_x^2=0.0018\]

  1. Pooled Variance (Intra-Sack Variance)

The Weight Variance in each sack is in the data frame SampVar with its corresponding sack number.

peste %>% group_by(nemoone) %>% summarise(variance=round(var(vazne.peste),4))->SampVar
knitr::kable(SampVar[1:5,])
nemoone variance
1 0.0346
2 0.0503
3 0.0336
4 0.0540
5 0.0428

Now we take an average over these sample variances to derive the pooled variance. were gonna use the pooled variance to later on calcualte value of F.

Sp2=round(mean(SampVar$variance),4)

Thus, The pooled variance is:

\[s_p^2=0.0426\]

  1. Calculating F

\[F=(ns_x^2)/s_p^2\]

where n is the number of samples per sack/nemoone.

n=max(peste$shomare)

F=n*Sx2/Sp2

now given the degrees of freedom within samples (\(90*109\)) and within sacks(\(90-1\)), using the F distribution we can findout whether F is in the left 95% of the distribution(\(H_0\) being correct) or not. For these values, the critical point of 95% is arount \(F(0.95)=1.35\).

Thus \(H_0\) is wrong and the pistachios are not homogenously distributed amongst the bags.

5.2 ANOVA Implementation

This time, we will use the aov() function.

fit<-aov(peste$vazne.peste~factor(peste$nemoone))
summary(fit)

6. Smiling vs.Size

First we prepare our data by adding a column of a nominal variable, Size. If a pistachios weight is in the upper or lower quantile of the distribution, then its considered Big/Small, aslo the two quantiles in the middle are Medium sized.

q=quantile(peste$vazne.peste)
peste %>% mutate(Size=ifelse(vazne.peste<q[2]|vazne.peste>q[4],"Big/Small","Medium"))->peste

We have two random variables, Size and naakhandan. the goal is to findout whether the distribution of naankhandan pistachios differs with size.

In each of the bags, well count the number of naakhandan pistachios for both Medium and Big/Small types.

assuming that each bag represents one sample, then well have 90 samples of number of nakhandan pistachios for both of the sizes explained before.

being naakhandan or not for each pistachio is a trial, having 110 pistachios in each bag, makes the number of naakhandans a multinomial variable. Since the number of pestachios per bags are large, we can assume that this number has a normal distribution. Thus, well be able to take a t.test on it.

\(H_0: \quad \mu_1>\mu_2 \quad\): This means that the Small/Big pistachios are more likely to be naakhandan. \(H_0: \quad \mu_1<\mu_2 \quad\): This means that the Small/Big pistachios are more likely to be naakhandan.

peste %>% group_by(Size,nemoone) %>% summarize(Number=sum(naakhandan))->Test
t.test(Test$Number~Test$Size,"greater")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Test$Number by Test$Size
## t = 0.71589, df = 175.1, p-value = 0.475
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.2928073  0.6261407
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Big/Small    mean in group Medium 
##                1.788889                1.622222

The p-value is high, so we cant determine whether \(H_0\) is correct or not. Lets take a look at the boxplot:

highchart() %>% 
  hc_add_series_boxplot(Test$Number,
                        by=Test$Size,name="Nakhandan Pistachios") %>% 
  hc_title(text="Medium vs Small/Large Sized pistachios smile comparission") %>% 
  hc_add_theme(hc_theme_google()) %>% 
  hc_xAxis(title=list(text="Bags")) %>% 
  hc_yAxis(title=list(text="Number of the not smiling pistachios per nemoone"))

we can see that the variance of these sets are somehow different. lets see if we can proove anything using an anova test with the following hypothesis:

\(H_0: \quad \mu_1=\mu_2 \quad\): This means that the likelihood of being naakhandan does not differ acording to size. \(H_0: \quad \mu_1\neq\mu_2 \quad\): This means that the likelihood of being naakhandan differs acording to size.

fit<-aov(Test$Number~Test$Size)
summary(fit)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## Test$Size     1    1.2   1.250   0.513  0.475
## Residuals   178  434.1   2.439

Again, the F is not significantly big and the Probability of its values isnt small enough for aus to able to conclude anything.

However, if we change our method of grouping to the following, well see a noticable change.

A big pistachio is the one with the big seed, so we call the upper half of the seed weight distribution Big and the lower half Small. By applying the same functions, we see that this time, \(H_0\) is not correct and the small pistachios are more likely to be naakhandan!

7.1 Shell Weight And Core weight: Does It Take A Bigger Shell TO Cover A Bigger Seed? (OstadPasand1 !)

A pistachios seed is big if its in the upper half of vazne.maghz distribution, and is small otherwise. Well compare the shell weight distribution for big/small seeds.

qu=quantile(peste$vazne.maghz)
peste %>% mutate(SeedSize=(ifelse(vazne.maghz>qu[3],"Large","Small")),
                 ShellWeight=round(vazne.peste-vazne.maghz,2)) %>% 
  filter(ShellWeight>0, ShellWeight<0.5)-> peste2

highchart() %>% 
  hc_add_series_density(density(filter(peste2,SeedSize=="Small")$ShellWeight),name="Small Seed") %>% 
  hc_add_series_density(density(filter(peste2,SeedSize=="Large")$ShellWeight),name="Large Seed") %>% 
  hc_title(text="Shell Weight distribution comparision according to seed size") %>% 
  hc_add_theme(hc_theme_google())

Well take a t.test to find out if our Zero hypothesis is ture or not.

\[H_0: \quad \mu_1=\mu2\] \[H_1: \quad \mu_1\neq\mu_2\]

where \(\mu_i\) is the mean shell weight for group i.

t.test(peste2$ShellWeight~peste2$SeedSize)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test

Since p-value is big, our data isnt sufficient to approve or disapprove the null hypothesis.

7.2 A More Precise investigation on Not-Smiling and Pistachios weight? (OstadPasand2 !)

In part 2, we concluded that the pistachios size, might have nothing to with not-smiling, since the p-value was high. Now lets take the Seed Weight into account. We expect big pistachios with small seeds to have a bigger shell, and having a big shell, might mean that the shell has covered the seed completely, which can be correlated with being naakhandan.

we have 2 explanatory variables, Seed Size and Pistachio Size, each taking 2 possible values. Thus, We have 4 types of pistachios. lets findout whether the distribution of naakhandan pistachios is homogeneous amongst these types.

There are 90 numerators, each containing 110 samples. and each of these samples are one of the four types below:

Large/Small Pistachio / Medium Seed Large/Small Pistachio / Large/Small Seed Medium Pistachio / Medium Seed Medium Pistachio / Large/Small Seed

This condition calls for a 2-way anova test.

qu=quantile(peste$vazne.maghz)
peste %>% mutate(Sizem=ifelse(vazne.maghz<qu[2]|vazne.maghz>qu[4],"Big/Small","Medium"))%>% 
  group_by(Size,Sizem,nemoone) %>% summarise(num=sum(naakhandan)) ->peste1
fit1<-aov(peste1$num~peste1$Size*peste1$Sizem)
summary(fit1)
##                           Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## peste1$Size                1    0.6    0.63   0.554  0.457    
## peste1$Sizem               1    1.0    1.00   0.888  0.347    
## peste1$Size:peste1$Sizem   1  123.7  123.67 109.545 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals                356  401.9    1.13                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

as we can see, when both pistachio and seed size are taken into account, F is significanty big and thus, \(H_0\) is wrong. \(H_0\) was the hypothesis which stated that all four types had the same disribution of nakhandaan pistachios.

Lets take a look at the distribution:

peste1 %>% mutate(Type=paste(Size,Sizem))->peste1
highchart() %>%
  hc_add_series_boxplot(peste1$num,by=peste1$Type,name="Number of Naakhandan Samples") %>% 
  hc_add_theme(hc_theme_google()) %>% 
  hc_title(text="Numbe of naakhandan pistachios according to pistachio and it's seed size")

It can be seen that if the shell (difference of pistachio and its seed) is certainly Small/Big, which happens when of the variables is Big/Small and the other is medium, then no nakhandan sample occures.
